  <datafield tag="245" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Insulator–metal transition in 1T′-MoS 2 under uniaxial strain</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="260" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="c">2015-11-06</subfield>
    <subfield code="t">published</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="300" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">7</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">First principles calculations have been performed to investigate the electronic properties of 1T′-MoS 2 under uniaxial strain. Insulator–metal transition (IMT) occurs when 1T′-MoS 2 is stretched uniaxially. For strain perpendicular to the zigzag chains of Mo atoms ( <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></msub></math> ), the critical strain for the IMT is 3.0%, while it reaches 4.8% for strain along the y direction. The IMT is due to the dropping of the state of the conduction band at the X point (CX) in the Brillouin zone, which is formed by the <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>−</mo><msup><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></msub></math> orbitals of Mo atoms in the stretched Mo–Mo bonds and shows antibonding character. The x projection of the Mo–Mo bonds is rather larger than their y projection, leading to the much smaller critical <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></msub></math> for the IMT. In comparison with 1T′-MoS 2 under biaxial strain ( <math altimg="si19.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub></math> ), although the CX state drops more rapidly than that under x strain, the critical <math altimg="si19.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub></math> is even larger than the critical <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></msub></math> , which is because the larger structural distortion under biaxial strain also induces great dropping of the valence band maximum. Moreover, uniaxial strain may be used for fine tuning of the critical electric field for the topological phase transition in 1T′-MoS 2 , which increases monotonically as a function of the strain.</subfield>
